# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brooklyn
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The **14th Regiment New York State Militia** (also called the **14th Brooklyn Chasseurs** and officially known during the American Civil War as **84th New York Volunteer Infantry Regiment**) was a volunteer militia regiment from the City of Brooklyn, New York.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] It is primarily known for its service in the American Civil War from April 1861 to 6 May 1864, although it later served in the Spanish–American War and World War I (as part of the 106th Regiment).
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] In the Civil War, the regiment was made up of a majority of abolitionists from the Brooklyn area.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Wood and later by Colonel Edward Brush Fowler.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn was involved in heavy fighting, including most major engagements of the Eastern Theater.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Their engagements included the First and Second Battles of Bull Run, the Battle of Antietam, Fredericksburg, Chancellorsville, Gettysburg, The Wilderness, and Spotsylvania Court House.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] During the war, the men of the 14th Brooklyn were well known by both armies and throughout the country for their hard drill, hard fighting, and constant refusal to stand down from a fight.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] During their three years of service they never withdrew from battle in unorderly fashion.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] On 7 December 1861, the State of New York officially changed the regiment's designation to the 84th New York Volunteer Infantry (and its unit histories are sometimes found under this designation).
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] But at the unit's request and because of the fame attained by the unit at First Bull Run, the United States Army continued to refer to it as the 14th.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn received its nickname, the "Red Legged Devils", during the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Referring to the regiment's colorful red trousers as the regiment repeatedly charged up Henry House Hill, Confederate General Thomas J.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] "Stonewall" Jackson yelled to his men, "Hold on Boys!
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] In the early part of the war, when the 14th Brooklyn was in General Walter Phelps' brigade, the brigade was named "Iron Brigade".
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] It would later become known as the "Eastern Iron Brigade" after John Gibbon's Black Hat Brigade was given the name "Western Iron Brigade".
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] At the conclusion of the war, all members of the "Eastern" or "First" Iron Brigade were given medals for their service within the Iron Brigade.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The Fourteenth Regiment New York State Militia was officially constituted on 13 May 1847 when the New York State Legislature consolidated individual militia companies into regiments.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] It was organized on 5 July 1847 with two companies: Company A, the Union Blues, and Company B, the Washington Guards.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Companies C to H were organized in February 1848.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] While the Fourteenth Regiment's purpose was to protect the city of Brooklyn and surrounding areas, in its early history it was more of a social club, where men of venerable lineage could train in military tactics and spend the weekends with other militiamen.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The regiment used the armory at Henry and Cranberry Streets as its headquarters.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] On 4 June 1854, a portion of the 14th Regiment, under the command of Colonel Jesse C.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Smith, was called to help suppress a riot caused by an anti-Catholic street preacher referring to himself as "the Angel Gabriel." In the so-called Angel Gabriel Riot, the regiment assisted the police in making a number of arrests.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] In early 1861, the 14th was called several times to the Naval Yard "in anticipation of an attack ... by Rebel sympathizers".
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] In 1860, the United States Zouave Cadets traveling drill team of Chicago, under the command of Colonel Elmer E.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The officers and men of the 14th Brooklyn were so impressed with the drill and uniforms of the drill team that they decided to take on a similar version of the French military uniform known as the *"Chasseur"* uniform.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] This uniform remained their battle dress uniform throughout their term of service in the American Civil War.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Brooklyn paid to keep the regiment in this uniform, and it remained one of the few regiments not to don the all blue standard Union military uniform.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] After the firing at Fort Sumter and President Abraham Lincoln's proclamation for volunteers to suppress the rebellion, the 14th volunteered themselves for a period of three years.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Wood telegraphed Washington that his regiment was prepared, but New York Governor Edwin D.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Morgan refused to send them (apparently for political motives).
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Colonel Wood then went to Washington and along with Congressman Moses F.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Odell explained the situation and as a result, President Lincoln directly ordered the regiment into action.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The regiment became a personal favorite of Lincoln.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Whenever the President was in the area of the regiment, he would attempt to pay them a visit.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] He would ask for the 14th Brooklyn to act as his personal guards when in camp or near the battle field.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Because of this attention by the President, the 14th Brooklyn was nicknamed *"Lincoln's Pups"* or *"Lincoln's Pets"*, a name the regiment would later shed after the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] President Lincoln gave a speech to them when the regiment mustered out in 1864, thanking them for their fine and honorable service to the United States.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn Regiment left New York on 18 May 1861 (except for Companies I and K, which joined it in July 1861), arriving in Washington, D.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] It was officially mustered into United States service by General Irvin McDowell on 23 May 1861 and initially served at and near Washington.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The typical uniform of a Union Soldier was that of a four-button blue sack coat, light kersey blue wool trousers and a blue cap (bummer, or forage cap).
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] At the beginning of the war both the Union and Confederate armies had a variety of uniforms within their regiments.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] As the war continued, the Union Army began to standardize the uniform worn by its regiments.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] By early 1862 most Union regiments were wearing blue.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] However, Brooklyn paid for and outfitted the 14th Brooklyn throughout the war, keeping them wearing their unique chasseur-style uniform for all three years of their service.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The headgear worn by the 14th Brooklyn was a navy blue and red kepi.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The top of the cap was covered in dark navy blue and the lower half by a dark red with a band of blue around the bottom of the cap.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Upon the front of the cap the regiment had the number '14' and above it was the company designation.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] On the sides of the caps were New York state buttons holding the chin strap onto the kepi.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] At the First Battle of Bull Run the 14th were issued havelocks, a white material that fitted over the kepis and had a long piece of cloth that hung down below over the neck.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The idea was to catch air and cool the neck of the soldier.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The havelocks proved ineffective as headgear, however many were used as bandages on the battlefield.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The tunics worn by the 14th Brooklyn were a beautiful combination of red and dark blue adorned with small gold buttons running up and the center of the chest.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The tunic was made with a red false vest with 14 buttons closing the vest.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Over the false vest was a dark blue shell with 14 buttons on either side of the shell.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Some later models of the jacket did away with the false vest and actually sewed the vest into the shell making it a complete jacket.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] On the jacket were chevrons on the lower arms symbolizing light infantry.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Earlier recruits also were issued "Shoulder-Knots" composed of thick red fabric that were attached with thread on one end and a gold button on the other.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The trousers worn by the 14th were very similar to that of the Zouave pantaloons, the only difference being that they were not as baggy as the Zouave pantaloons.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] At the bottom of the trousers the 14th wore gaiters or leggings with seven gold buttons on each gaiter symbolizing the number 14.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Fowler wrote a letter home commenting on the regiment, a bit about the uniforms, and the tactics in which he had to use.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] It was later placed in the regimental history.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] At the First Battle of Bull Run, the 14th Brooklyn was assigned to the First Brigade (commanded by Col.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] David Hunter's Second Division in General Irwin McDowell's Army of Northeastern Virginia.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The Regiment was ordered up to Henry House Hill to reinforce the 1st Minnesota Volunteer Infantry Regiment and the 11th New York Volunteer Infantry Regiment, the "Fire Zouaves".
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] These regiments had been ordered to support two batteries of cannon under the command of Captains Charles Griffin and James B.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Before the arrival of the 14th Brooklyn at Henry House Hill, the 11th New York had withdrawn to the Manassas-Sudley Road under heavy assault and then fought off a flank attack from Confederate Colonel J.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] As the 14th Brooklyn moved up the hill, the 11th New York rallied and joined with the 14th to support the guns.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn, 11th New York, and 1st Minnesota were placed into position by Major William Farquhar Barry, McDowell's chief of artillery, at the crest of Henry House Hill.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] They were ordered to hold their position and assault if the opportunity was there, but were under no circumstances to leave the guns to the Confederates.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The three regiments and cannon found themselves confronting the 33rd Virginia Infantry on the left of Confederate General Thomas J.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Confusion soon erupted on the battlefield in front of them.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Thinking the 33rd Virginia, clad in dark blue frock coats and dark blue trousers, were the Union troops supporting the guns, Major Barry ordered Ricketts to hold his fire.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] This allowed the Virginians to charge the batteries and capture the guns.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn, however, rushed up the slope and drove the 33rd Virginia back, recapturing the two guns.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th then continued to fire into the left flank of Jackson's line, driving the 33rd Virginia back through the 2nd Virginia Infantry.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Under the pressure from the 14th Brooklyn, a large portion of the 2nd Virginia joined the retreating 33rd Virginia and the left of Jackson's line began to collapse.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] However, Jackson ordered the 4th and 27th Virginia forward.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] They were joined by the 49th Virginia Infantry, two companies of the 2nd Mississippi Infantry, and the 6th North Carolina Infantry.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] In hand-to-hand combat the New Yorkers were driven back to the Manassas-Sudley Road and Ricketts' battery and Griffin's two guns captured.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn, the 69th New York Militia and 11th New York would charge up Henry House Hill four times, in an effort to recapture Ricketts' and Griffin's cannon.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The other two regiments met with little success, but the 14th Brooklyn found gaps and weaknesses in the Confederate lines and exploited them.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn briefly took control of the two guns following one charge, only to be routed yet again by the Confederates.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The constant charging of the 14th Brooklyn's tactics caught the eye of General Jackson himself.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] This is when he made his famous statement to his troops: *"Hold on Boys!
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Here come those Red Legged Devils again!"* With that the regiment received its nickname the "Red Legged Devils".
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] While the 14th Brooklyn and 11th New York Volunteer Infantry were briefly in control of the two guns, the Louisiana Tigers advanced up the hill.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th and 11th fired upon the battalion from their superior position, causing significant losses.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The Tigers then fired their own rifles, and the majority of the 14th fell to their knees.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Encouraged by this, the Tigers dropped their rifles and took out their Bowie knives in an attempt to finish off the survivors.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] As the Tigers neared the crest of the hill, the 14th Brooklyn stood up.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Though both the 14th Brooklyn and the Tigers, who had left their rifles at the bottom of the hill, were poorly trained and lacked real wartime experience, a savage hand-to-hand fight began between the two units.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Though the Tigers fought with ferocity and determination, the 14th Brooklyn had the superior field position and eventually the Tigers retreated back down the hill.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] This brief confrontation permanently made the 14th Brooklyn and the Tigers rivals.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The efforts of the 14th Brooklyn, however, were in vain, and they were immediately flushed from the position yet again by the powerful Confederate counterattack.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The two guns would not be retaken again.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] As the Confederates launched their strong counterattack, the Union army panicked and fled.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] They had been startled by the fierce, brutal fighting that the Confederates had brought, it being completely unlike the riot quelling they had performed in the past.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] It is local legend that the 14th Brooklyn refused to flee with such blind abandon as the rest of the Union army, but rather were ordered off the field, but this has not been corroborated by any contemporary records.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] During the battle, the 14th Regiment suffered two officers and 21 men killed, 64 wounded, and 30 taken prisoner.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Ten of the wounded would die of their wounds.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Colonel Wood himself was wounded and captured by the enemy.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] After the First Battle of Bull Run, the State of New York decided to change the regiment's designation from 14th State Militia to 84th New York Volunteer Infantry.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The men of the regiment were displeased and began a letter campaign, joined by the citizens of Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Finally the men asked the help of General Irvin McDowell.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] At Second Bull Run the regiment again fought courageously, losing nearly 120 men.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] At Antietam, the 1st Division commanded by Brigadier General Abner Doubleday of the 1st Corps began their attack on the morning of 17 September 1862 from the North Woods.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Walter Phelps' Iron Brigade fought through the Miller Farm's cornfield.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Both Union and Confederate casualties at the cornfield were roughly 6,000.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] It was at the cornfield that famed nurse Clara Barton went onto the actual battlefield to help the wounded soldiers of the Union Army.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] According to a report from William Fox of the 107th New York, the brigade that composed of the 22nd New York, 24th New York, 30th New York, 14th Regiment (New York State Militia), and 2nd U.S.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Sharpshooters was the first to be called the "Eastern Iron Brigade" because of its brave fighting at South Mountain and Antietam.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] In the cornfield, the Eastern Iron Brigade followed the Western Brigade into battle early in the morning.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] While the rest of Phelp's brigade fell back, the 14th Brooklyn held its ground along with elements of the 6th Wisconsin of the Black Hats (Western Iron Brigade).
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] This effort combined into a mass of soldiers pushing the Confederates up to Dunker Church.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] These two regiments got further than any other Union Regiment during the attack in the cornfield.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] At Fredericksburg and Chancellorsville the 14th Brooklyn saw minor action during the major engagements.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The regiment was held in reserve and then used for a series of reconnaissance missions to find and assault the Confederate forces in and around the area.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] It was during this campaign that the Brigade proved that they truly were the "Iron Brigade of the East" During Chancellorsville the regiment saw a quick but highly deadly action alongside the Sixth Wisconsin in the Battle of Fitzhugh's Crossing.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th held the riverbank as the sixth Wisconsin attempted to cross the river in small wooden boats.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] It was after this campaign a little before the Battle of Gettysburg that the 14th and all the other regiments in the 1st Corps, 1st Division, 1st Brigade were transferred out.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th was transferred to the 1st Corps, 1st Division, 2nd Brigade.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn was the last regiment of the 2nd Brigade on the road to Gettysburg.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 2nd Brigade were the first Infantry units to fire their rifles and to set foot on the field 1 July 1863.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Reynolds rode up to the 2nd Brigade and urged them onto Gettysburg to support General John Buford's cavalry who were holding the Confederate forces at bay.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th dropped its packs on the Emmitsburg road and double-quicked across the field that General Pickett's men would attack on 3 July.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn arrived at McPherson's Woods and halted the Confederate advance, until the 1st Brigade of the 1st division arrived.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Once the Western Iron Brigade was online, Colonel E.B Fowler saw Confederate forces taking cover in an unfinished railroad cut to his right.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] He commanded his "Demi-Brigade" (14th Regiment & 95th NYVI) across the field to meet and clear out Davis' Confederate Brigade.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Held in reserve the 6th Wisconsin was ordered to support the 14th regiment and 95th NYVI into the cut.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Again the 14th and 6th were together working as they did in earlier engagements.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Into the cut the three regiments rushed, supporting each other equally on each other's flanks.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] One 14th Brooklyn soldier said of the Confederate defense of the railroad cut *"they fought with the ferocity of wildcats"* and the fight became a brawl of hand-to-hand combat.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The Federals who had taken a beating crossing the field in front of the railroad cut had their revenge.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The Confederates facing them finally realized their position was a death trap and surrendered themselves to Colonel E.B.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Fowler, and handed their flags over to the 14th Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Finally the Confederates were able to wheel artillery down and fire on the 14th's position in the railroad cut; the 14th marched out of the cut through the town of Gettysburg while the 11th corps came up to support the 1st corps so they could refit.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn had the honor of carrying General John F.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Reynolds' body from the field into the town of Gettysburg.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The regiment continued to fight for the remainder of the battle of Gettysburg.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] They are the only regiment to possess three monuments on the field of Gettysburg: at the railroad cut, at McPherson's woods, and on Culp's Hill.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The remainder of the fight was on Culp's Hill on the right flank of the Union army.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] They were called up to support General Greene who was losing his position to superior numbers.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn fought two days up there, and Greene later credited the 14th Brooklyn for helping save the entire Union army by saving the flank.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] In the early hours of 2 July 1863 the 14th Brooklyn was called down to the slope of Culp's Hill.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Cantine, one of General Greene's aides, met the regiment and guided Col.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Fowler and the regiment to its position on the right of Greene's line.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] As Cantine led Fowler by some trees, a soldier stepped from the darkness and demanded Cantine's surrender.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Cantine dismounted from his horse and Fowler drew his pistol, and then there were a dozen or so shots from the woods.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Fowler hurried back to the regiment and formed it facing the woods.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Fowler then called for volunteers to scout the woods and report back, who may be at his front.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] James McQuire of company I, responded and disappeared into the woods or, as one 14th Brooklyn member recounts "in the teeth of flank fire", to find out who was there.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Cox returned with the word that McQuire had been wounded and that the troops in their front belonged to the 10th Virginia Regiment.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Colonel Fowler then ordered the regiment to fire a volley and thus charged his regiment into the woods.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Hand-to-hand fighting began, and the 14th pushed the Virginians out of the woods and sent them into a retreat.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn was called back up the hill after this action being relieved by the 137th Ny.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] They were there long enough to eat some food and then were immediately sent back down the hill to support the hill once again.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] On 3 July, the 14th Brooklyn's Position was further up the hill near the 149th New York.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] When the men of the 149th New York had heard that the 14th Brooklyn were coming down they studied them closely.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Prior to this the men of the 149th had heard that the 14th Brooklyn were "a bully fighting regiment" what they saw were young men with a "tidy and smart appearance".
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] In Later years the regiment was credited with saving the line and thus saving ammunition trains as well as the flank.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Brooklyn fought for another year, through the Battle of the Wilderness campaign and Spotsylvania.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The recruits who signed up and joined the regiment in 1862 were moved over to the 5th New York Veteran Volunteer Infantry Regiment.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] However, the recruits who went over to the 5th New York Veterans (Duryea Zouaves) wore their 14th Brooklyn uniform and formed their own company in the 5th.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The regiment mustered out at Fulton Ferry on 25 May 1864 to huge crowds who welcomed the regiment home after three years of service.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] During its three years in service, the regiment sustained 717 casualties, nearly 41% of its men.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Since the regiment's return from the battlefields of the American Civil War, the 14th was twice involved in service, first during the quarantine disturbances at Fire Island in September 1892, and throughout the Brooklyn motormen's strike in January 1895.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th was one of the few regiments selected in General Orders, No.8, General Headquarters, State of New York, dated Adjutant General Office, Albany, 27 April 1898, to enter United States Military service.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] At that time the regiment consisted of ten companies.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Upon receiving this order the regiment began recruiting to fill these companies as well as organize two additional ones.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th Regiment, Infantry, New York Volunteers was mustered into the service in May 1898 take part in the Spanish–American War.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The regiment was in Federal service for only four months and was detailed to camp service.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th did not reach the front lines, but made preparations for duty in Cuba, and the soldiers were in a "fine state of organization".
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] All of the 14th's officers and men were anxious to be involved the real fighting on the front lines, but this movement was deemed unnecessary by the government after considerable thought.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] On 1 May, the regiment was ordered to camp at Hempstead, Long Island New York.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The regiment then reported to Major General Charles F.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Roe, who was in command of the National Guard.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The 14th then mustered into service as follows: Companies A, G, K, and M on 13 May; the rest of its companies on 16 May.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] On 17 May, the regiment left Hempstead and proceeded by rail to Camp George H.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The regiment arrived and was assigned to the First Brigade, First Division, Third Army Corps on 29 May.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] On 5 September, the 14th Infantry received orders to muster out on corner of Eighth Avenue and Fifteenth Street, Brooklyn at the armory.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The men of the 14th left Anniston on 14 September and arrived in Brooklyn on 16 September.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] In 1893, the Eighth Avenue Armory was constructed for the regiment.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] They were mustered out United States service on 27 October 1898.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] The regiment entered the Spanish–American War as the 14th New York Infantry and many sons of veterans who fought during the American Civil War with the 14th Brooklyn enlisted with the 14th New York Infantry.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Following the Spanish–American War, 14th New York Infantry troops reinforced the 106th Infantry and fought in World War I.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Following the conclusion of the war, members of the 14th Regiment New York Veterans Association continued to hold monthly meetings.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Several battlefield memorials were erected over time.
[src:brooklyn/14th-brooklyn] Today members of reenactment units do the same to preserve the honor and memory of the 14th Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/1776-book] The text closely mirrors the original book, but omits or summarizes some parts deemed too long.
[src:brooklyn/1776-book] The Illustrated Edition comes with its own protective slipcase, decorated with *The Capture of the Hessians at Trenton, December 26, 1776* by John Trumbull and has a "fake watermark" of the Great Seal of the United States on the back and front.
[src:brooklyn/1776-book] The book is plain covered in blue with the golden embossed numbers "1776".
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:brooklyn/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:brooklyn/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:brooklyn/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:brooklyn/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:brooklyn/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:brooklyn/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:brooklyn/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:brooklyn/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:brooklyn/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:brooklyn/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:brooklyn/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:brooklyn/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The borough, as Kings County, at 37,339.9 inhabitants per square mile (14,417.0/km2), is the second most densely populated county in the U.S. after Manhattan (New York County), and the most populous county in the state, as of 2022.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In the 2020 United States census, the borough had a population of 2,736,074.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Had Brooklyn remained an independent city on Long Island, it would now be the fourth most populous American city after the rest of New York City, Los Angeles, and Chicago.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn, named after the Dutch town of Breukelen in the Netherlands, was founded by the Dutch in the 17th century and grew into a busy port city on New York Harbor by the 19th century.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The borough continues to maintain a distinct culture.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Many Brooklyn neighborhoods are ethnic enclaves.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] With Jews forming around a fifth of its population, the borough has been described as one of the main global hubs for Jewish culture.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn's official motto, displayed on the borough seal and flag, is *Een Draght Mackt Maght*, which translates from early modern Dutch as "In unity there is strength".
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Educational institutions in Brooklyn include the City University of New York's Brooklyn College, Medgar Evers College, and College of Technology, as well as Pratt Institute, Long Island University, and the New York University Tandon School of Engineering.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In sports, basketball's Brooklyn Nets, and New York Liberty play at the Barclays Center.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In the first decades of the 21st century, Brooklyn has experienced a renaissance as a destination for hipsters, with associated gentrification, dramatic house-price increases, and a decrease in housing affordability.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Some new developments are now required to include affordable housing units.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Since the 2010s, parts of Brooklyn have evolved into a hub for entrepreneurship, high-technology startup firms, postmodern art, and design.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The name Brooklyn is derived from the original Dutch town of Breukelen.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] This form is made up of the words *broeck*, meaning bog or marshland, and *lede*, meaning small (dug) water stream, specifically in peat areas.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Breuckelen on the American continent was established in 1646, and the name first appeared in print in 1663.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Over the past two millennia, the name of the ancient town in Holland has been *Bracola*, *Broccke*, *Brocckede*, *Broiclede*, *Brocklandia*, *Broekclen*, *Broikelen*, *Breuckelen*, and finally *Breukelen*.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The New Amsterdam settlement of *Breuckelen* also went through many spelling variations, including *Breucklyn*, *Breuckland*, *Brucklyn*, *Broucklyn*, *Brookland*, *Brockland*, *Brocklin*, and *Brookline/Brook-line*.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] There have been so many variations of the name that its origin has been debated; some have claimed *breuckelen* means "broken land".
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The current name, however, is the one that best reflects its meaning.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The county's name, **Kings County**, was named after King Charles II of England, who ruled from 1660 to 1685.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The history of European settlement in Brooklyn spans more than 350 years.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The Dutch were the first Europeans to settle Long Island's western edge, which was then largely inhabited by the Lenape, an Algonquian-speaking American Indian tribe often referred to in European documents by a variation of the place name "Canarsie".
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Bands were associated with place names, but the colonists thought their names represented different tribes.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The *Breuckelen* settlement was named after Breukelen in the Netherlands; it was part of New Netherland.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The colony's capital of New Amsterdam, across the East River, obtained its charter in 1653.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The neighborhood of Marine Park was home to North America's first tide mill.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] It was built by the Dutch, and the foundation can be seen today.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] But the area was not formally settled as a town.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Many incidents and documents relating to this period are in Gabriel Furman's 1824 compilation.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Present-day Brooklyn left Dutch hands after the English conquest of New Netherland in 1664, which sparked the Second Anglo-Dutch War.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] New Netherland was taken in a naval action, and the English renamed the new capture for their naval commander, James, Duke of York, brother of the then monarch King Charles II and future king himself as King James II.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn became a part of the West Riding of York Shire in the Province of New York, one of the Middle Colonies in England's North American colonies.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] On November 1, 1683, *Kings County* was partitioned from the West Riding of York Shire, containing the six old Dutch towns on southwestern Long Island, as one of the "original twelve counties".
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] This tract of land was recognized as a political entity for the first time, and the municipal groundwork was laid for a later expansive idea of a Brooklyn identity.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Lacking the patroon and tenant farmer system established along the Hudson River Valley, this agricultural county unusually came to have one of the highest percentages of slaves among the population in the "Original Thirteen Colonies" along the Atlantic Ocean eastern coast of North America.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] On August 27, 1776, the Battle of Long Island (also known as the 'Battle of Brooklyn') was fought, the first major engagement fought in the American Revolutionary War after independence was declared, and the largest of the entire conflict.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] British troops forced the Continental Army under George Washington off the heights near the modern sites of Green-Wood Cemetery, Prospect Park, and Grand Army Plaza.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Washington, viewing particularly fierce fighting at the Gowanus Creek and Old Stone House from atop a hill near the west end of present-day Atlantic Avenue, was reported to have emotionally exclaimed: "What brave men I must this day lose!".
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The fortified American positions at Brooklyn Heights consequently became untenable and were evacuated a few days later, leaving the British in control of New York Harbor.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] While Washington's defeat on the battlefield cast early doubts on his ability as the commander, the tactical withdrawal of all his troops and supplies across the East River in a single night is now seen by historians as one of his most brilliant triumphs.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The British controlled the surrounding region for the duration of the war, as New York City was soon occupied and became their military and political base of operations in British-held North America for the remainder of the conflict.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The British set up a system of prison ships off the coast of Brooklyn in Wallabout Bay.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] More American prisoners of war died on these prison ships than were killed in action on all the battlefield engagements of the war combined.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] One result of the Treaty of Paris in 1783 was the evacuation of the British from New York City, which was celebrated by New Yorkers into the 20th century.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The first half of the 19th century saw the beginning of the development of urban areas on the economically strategic East River shore of Kings County, facing the adolescent City of New York confined to Manhattan Island.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The New York Navy Yard operated in Wallabout Bay (border between Fort Greene and Williamsburg) during the 19th century and two-thirds of the 20th century.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The first center of urbanization sprang up in the Town of Brooklyn, directly across from Lower Manhattan, which saw the incorporation of the Village of Brooklyn in 1816.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Reliable steam ferry service across the East River to Fulton Landing converted Brooklyn Heights into a commuter town for Wall Street.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Ferry Road to Jamaica Pass became Fulton Street to East New York.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Town and Village were combined to form the first, kernel incarnation of the City of Brooklyn in 1834.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In a parallel development, the Town of Bushwick, farther up the river, saw the incorporation of the Village of Williamsburgh in 1827, which separated as the Town of Williamsburgh in 1840 and formed the short-lived City of Williamsburgh in 1851.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Industrial deconcentration in the mid-century was bringing shipbuilding and other manufacturing to the northern part of the county.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Each of the two cities and six towns in Kings County remained independent municipalities and purposely created non-aligning street grids with different naming systems.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] However, the East River shore was growing too fast for the three-year-old infant City of Williamsburg; it, along with its Town of Bushwick hinterland, was subsumed within a greater City of Brooklyn in 1855, subsequently dropping the 'h' from its name.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] By 1841, with the appearance of *The Brooklyn Eagle, and Kings County Democrat* published by Alfred G.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Stevens, the growing city across the East River from Manhattan was producing its own prominent newspaper.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] It later became the most popular and highest circulation afternoon paper in America.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Van Anden on April 19, 1842, and the paper was renamed *The Brooklyn Daily Eagle and Kings County Democrat* on June 1, 1846.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] On May 14, 1849, the name was shortened to *The Brooklyn Daily Eagle*; on September 5, 1938, it was further shortened to *Brooklyn Eagle*.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The establishment of the paper in the 1840s helped develop a separate identity for Brooklynites over the next century.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The borough's soon-to-be-famous National League baseball team, the Brooklyn Dodgers, also assisted with this.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Both major institutions were lost in the 1950s: the paper closed in 1955 after unsuccessful attempts at a sale following a reporters' strike, and the baseball team decamped for Los Angeles in a realignment of Major League Baseball in 1957.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Agitation against Southern slavery was stronger in Brooklyn than in New York, and under Republican leadership, the city was fervent in the Union cause in the Civil War.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] After the war the Henry Ward Beecher Monument was built downtown to honor a famous local abolitionist.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] A great victory arch was built at what was then the south end of town to celebrate the armed forces; this place is now called Grand Army Plaza.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The number of people living in Brooklyn grew rapidly early in the 19th century.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The city's population was 25,000 in 1834, but the police department comprised only 12 men on the day shift and another 12 on the night shift.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Every time a rash of burglaries broke out, officials blamed burglars from New York City.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Finally, in 1855, a modern police force was created, employing 150 men.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Voters complained of inadequate protection and excessive costs.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In 1857, the state legislature merged the Brooklyn force with that of New York City.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Fervent in the Union cause, the city of Brooklyn played a major role in supplying troops and materiel for the American Civil War.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The best-known regiment to be sent off to war from the city was the 14th Brooklyn *"Red Legged Devils"*.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] They fought from 1861 to 1864, wore red the entire war, and were the only regiment named after a city.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] President Abraham Lincoln called them into service, making them part of a handful of three-year enlisted soldiers in April 1861.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Unlike other regiments during the American Civil War, the 14th wore a uniform inspired by the French Chasseurs, a light infantry used for quick assaults.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] As a seaport and a manufacturing center, Brooklyn was well prepared to contribute to the Union's strengths in shipping and manufacturing.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The two combined in shipbuilding; the ironclad *Monitor* was built in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn is referred to as the twin city of New York in the 1883 poem, "The New Colossus" by Emma Lazarus, which appears on a plaque inside the Statue of Liberty.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The poem calls New York Harbor "the air-bridged harbor that twin cities frame".
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] As a twin city to New York, it played a role in national affairs that was later overshadowed by decades of subordination by its old partner and rival.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Contiguous to the Heights, the less exclusive South Brooklyn was home to longtime civic leader James S.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Stranahan, who became known (often derisively) as the "Baron Haussmann of Brooklyn" for championing Prospect Park and other public works.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Economic growth continued, propelled by immigration and industrialization, and Brooklyn established itself as the third-most populous American city for much of the 19th century.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The waterfront from Gowanus to Greenpoint was developed with piers and factories.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Industrial access to the waterfront was improved by the Gowanus Canal and the canalized Newtown Creek.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] USS *Monitor* was the most famous product of the large and growing shipbuilding industry of Williamsburg.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] By century's end, Dean Alvord's Prospect Park South development (adjacent to the village of Flatbush) would serve as the template for contemporaneous "Victorian Flatbush" micro-neighborhoods and the post-consolidation emergence of outlying districts, such as Midwood and Marine Park.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Along with Oak Park, Illinois, it also presaged the automobile and commuter rail-driven vogue for more remote prewar suburban communities, such as Garden City, New York and Montclair, New Jersey.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The rapidly growing population needed more water, so the City built centralized waterworks, including the Ridgewood Reservoir.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The municipal Police Department, however, was abolished in 1854 in favor of a Metropolitan force covering also New York and Westchester Counties.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In 1865 the Brooklyn Fire Department (BFD) also gave way to the new Metropolitan Fire District.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Throughout this period the peripheral towns of Kings County, far from Manhattan and even from urban Brooklyn, maintained their rustic independence.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The only municipal change seen was the secession of the eastern section of the Town of Flatbush as the Town of New Lots in 1852.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The building of rail links such as the Brighton Beach Line in 1878 heralded the end of this isolation.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The Brooklyn Bridegrooms played professional baseball at Washington Park in the convenient suburb of Park Slope and elsewhere.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Early in the next century, under their new name of Brooklyn Dodgers, they brought baseball to Ebbets Field, beyond Prospect Park.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Racetracks, amusement parks, and beach resorts opened in Brighton Beach, Coney Island, and elsewhere in the southern part of the county.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Toward the end of the 19th century, the City of Brooklyn experienced its final, explosive growth spurt.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Park Slope was rapidly urbanized, with its eastern summit soon emerging as the city's third "Gold Coast" district alongside Brooklyn Heights and The Hill; notable residents of the era included American Chicle Company co-founder Thomas Adams Jr. and New York Central Railroad executive Clinton L.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] East of The Hill, Bedford-Stuyvesant coalesced as an upper middle class enclave for lawyers, shopkeepers, and merchants of German and Irish descent (notably exemplified by John C.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Kelley, a water meter magnate and close friend of President Grover Cleveland), with nearby Crown Heights gradually fulfilling an analogous role for the city's Jewish population as development continued through the early 20th century.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Northeast of Bedford-Stuyvesant, Bushwick (by now a working class, predominantly German district) established a considerable brewery industry; the so-called "Brewer's Row" encompassed 14 breweries operating in a 14-block area in 1890.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] On the southwestern waterfront of Kings County, railroads and industrialization spread to Sunset Park (then coterminous with the city's sprawling, sparsely populated Eighth Ward) and adjacent Bay Ridge (hitherto a resort-like subsection of the Town of New Utrecht).
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Within a decade, the city had annexed the Town of New Lots in 1886; the Towns of Flatbush, Gravesend and New Utrecht in 1894; and the Town of Flatlands in 1896.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn had reached its natural municipal boundaries at the ends of Kings County.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn elected a mayor from 1834 until 1898, after which it was consolidated into the City of Greater New York, the second mayor of which (1902–1903), Seth Low, had been Mayor of Brooklyn from 1882 to 1885.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Since 1898, Brooklyn has, in place of a separate mayor, elected a Borough President.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In 1883, the Brooklyn Bridge was completed, transportation to Manhattan was no longer by water only, and the City of Brooklyn's ties to the City of New York were strengthened.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Andrew Haswell Green and other progressives said yes, and eventually, they prevailed against the *Daily Eagle* and other conservative forces.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In 1894, residents of Brooklyn and the other counties voted by a slight majority to merge, effective in 1898.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Kings County retained its status as one of New York State's counties, but the loss of Brooklyn's separate identity as a city was met with consternation by some residents at the time.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Many newspapers of the day called the merger the "Great Mistake of 1898".
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn is 97 square miles (250 km2) in area, of which 71 square miles (180 km2) is land (73%), and 26 square miles (67 km2) is water (27%); the borough is the second-largest by land area among the New York City's boroughs.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] However, Kings County, coterminous with Brooklyn, is New York State's fourth-smallest county by land area and third-smallest by total area.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn lies at the southwestern end of Long Island, and the borough's western border constitutes the island's western tip.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] To the east of Brooklyn lies the borough of Queens, which contains John F.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Kennedy International Airport in that borough's Jamaica neighborhood, approximately two miles from the border of Brooklyn's East New York neighborhood.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Under the Köppen climate classification, Brooklyn experiences a humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*), with partial shielding from the Appalachian Mountains and moderating influences from the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn receives plentiful precipitation all year round, with nearly 50 in (1,300 mm) yearly.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Snowfall is most common in February with around 20–21 centimeters or 8.3–8.5 inches.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The area averages 234 days with at least some sunshine annually, and averages 57% of possible sunshine annually, accumulating 2,535 hours of sunshine per annum.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn lies in the USDA plant hardiness zone 7b.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn's neighborhoods are dynamic in ethnic composition.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] For example, the early to mid-20th century, Brownsville had a majority of Jewish residents; since the 1970s it has been majority African American.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Midwood during the early 20th century was filled with ethnic Irish, then filled with Jewish residents for nearly 50 years, and is slowly becoming a Pakistani enclave.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn's most populous racial group, white, declined from 97.2% in 1930 to 46.9% by 1990.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The borough attracts people previously living in other cities in the United States.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Of these, most come from Chicago, Detroit, San Francisco, Washington, D.C., Baltimore, Philadelphia, Boston, Cincinnati, and Seattle.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In 2010, 51.6% of the population was counted as members of religious congregations.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In 2014, there were 914 religious organizations in Brooklyn, the 10th most of all counties in the nation.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn contains dozens of distinct neighborhoods representing many of the major culturally identified groups found within New York City.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Over 600,000 Jews, particularly Orthodox and Hasidic Jews, have become concentrated in such historically Jewish areas as Borough Park, Williamsburg, and Midwood, where there are many yeshivas, synagogues, and kosher restaurants, as well as a variety of Jewish businesses.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Other notable religious Jewish neighborhoods with a longstanding cultural lineage include Canarsie, Sea Gate, and Crown Heights, home to the Chabad world headquarters.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Neighborhoods with largely defunct yet historically notable Jewish populations include central Flatbush, East Flatbush, Brownsville, East New York, Bensonhurst and Sheepshead Bay (particularly its Madison subsection).
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Many hospitals in Brooklyn were started by Jewish charities, including Maimonides Medical Center in Borough Park and Brookdale Hospital in East Flatbush.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] According to the American Jewish Population Project in 2020, Brooklyn was home to over 480,000 Jews.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In 2023, the UJA-Federation of New York estimated that Brooklyn is home to 462,000 Jews, a large decrease compared to the 561,000 estimated in 2011.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Many non-Orthodox Jews (ranging from observant members of various denominations to atheists of Jewish cultural heritage) are concentrated in Ditmas Park and Park Slope, with smaller observant and culturally Jewish populations in Brooklyn Heights, Cobble Hill, Brighton Beach, and Coney Island.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Over 200,000 Chinese Americans live throughout the southern parts of Brooklyn, primarily concentrated in Sunset Park, Bensonhurst, Gravesend, and Homecrest.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn is the borough that is home to the highest number of Chinatowns in New York City.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The largest concentration is in Sunset Park along 8th Avenue, which has become known for its Chinese culture since the opening of the now-defunct Winley Supermarket in 1986 spurred widespread settlement in the area.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Many Chinese restaurants can be found throughout Sunset Park, and the area hosts a popular Chinese New Year celebration.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn's African American and Caribbean communities are spread throughout much of Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn's West Indian community is concentrated in the Crown Heights, Flatbush, East Flatbush, Kensington, and Canarsie neighborhoods in central Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn is home to the largest community of West Indians outside of the Caribbean.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Although the largest West Indian groups in Brooklyn are Jamaicans, Guyanese and Haitians, there are West Indian immigrants from nearly every part of the Caribbean.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Crown Heights and Flatbush are home to many of Brooklyn's West Indian restaurants and bakeries.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn has an annual, celebrated Carnival in the tradition of pre-Lenten celebrations in the islands.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Started by natives of Trinidad and Tobago, the West Indian Labor Day Parade takes place every Labor Day on Eastern Parkway.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The Brooklyn Academy of Music also holds the DanceAfrica festival in late May, featuring street vendors and dance performances showcasing food and culture from all parts of Africa.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Since the opening of the IND Fulton Street Line in 1936, Bedford-Stuyvesant has been home to one of the most famous African American communities in the United States.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Working-class communities remain prevalent in Brownsville, East New York and Coney Island, while remnants of similar communities in Prospect Heights, Fort Greene and Clinton Hill have endured amid widespread gentrification.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The borough's Hispanic population diversified after the 1965 Hart-Cellar Act loosened restrictions on immigration from elsewhere in Latin America.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Bushwick has since emerged as the largest hub of Brooklyn's Hispanic American community.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Like other Hispanic neighborhoods in New York City, Bushwick has an established Puerto Rican presence, along with an influx of many Dominicans, South Americans, Central Americans and Mexicans.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] As nearly 80% of Bushwick's population is Hispanic, its residents have created many businesses to support their various national and distinct traditions in food and other items.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Sunset Park's population is 42% Hispanic, made up of these various ethnic groups.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn's main Hispanic groups are Puerto Ricans, Mexicans, Dominicans and Ecuadorians; they are spread out throughout the borough.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Puerto Ricans and Dominicans are predominant in Bushwick, Williamsburg's South Side and East New York.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Mexicans (especially from the state of Puebla) now predominate alongside Chinese immigrants in Sunset Park, although remnants of the neighborhood's once-substantial postwar Puerto Rican and Dominican communities continue to reside below 39th Street.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] A Panamanian enclave exists in Crown Heights.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn is also home to many Russians and Ukrainians, who are mainly concentrated in the areas of Brighton Beach and Sheepshead Bay.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brighton Beach features many Russian and Ukrainian businesses and has been nicknamed *Little Russia* and *Little Odessa*, respectively.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In the 1970s, Soviet Jews won the right to immigrate, and many ended up in Brighton Beach.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In recent years, the non-Jewish Russian and Ukrainian communities of Brighton Beach have grown, and the area is now home to a diverse collection of immigrants from across the former USSR.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Smaller concentrations of Russian and Ukrainian Americans are scattered elsewhere in south Brooklyn, including Bay Ridge, Bensonhurst, Homecrest, Coney Island, and Mill Basin.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] A growing community of Uzbek Americans have settled alongside them in recent years due to their ability to speak Russian.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn's Polish inhabitants are historically concentrated in Greenpoint, home to Little Poland.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Other longstanding settlements in Borough Park and Sunset Park have endured, while more recent immigrants are scattered throughout the southern parts of Brooklyn alongside the Russian and Ukrainian American communities.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Despite widespread migration to Staten Island and more suburban areas in metropolitan New York throughout the postwar era, notable concentrations of Italian Americans continue to reside in the neighborhoods of Bensonhurst, Dyker Heights, Bay Ridge, Bath Beach and Gravesend.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] All of the aforementioned neighborhoods have retained Italian restaurants, bakeries, delicatessens, pizzerias, cafes and social clubs.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] In the early 20th century, many Lebanese and Syrian Christians settled around Atlantic Avenue west of Flatbush Avenue in Boerum Hill; more recently, this area has evolved into a Yemeni commercial district.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brighton Beach is home to a growing Pakistani American community, while Midwood is home to *Little Pakistan* along Coney Island Avenue (recently co-named Muhammad Ali Jinnah Way).
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Pakistani Independence Day is celebrated every year with parades and parties on Coney Island Avenue.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Just to the north, Kensington is one of New York's several emerging Bangladeshi enclaves.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Third-, fourth- and fifth-generation Irish Americans can be found throughout Brooklyn, with moderate concentrations enduring in the neighborhoods of Windsor Terrace, Park Slope, Bay Ridge, Marine Park and Gerritsen Beach.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Historical communities also existed in Vinegar Hill and other waterfront industrial neighborhoods, such as Greenpoint and Sunset Park.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Paralleling the Italian American community, many moved to Staten Island and suburban areas in the postwar era.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] While not as extensive as the Indian American population in Queens, younger professionals of Asian Indian origin are finding Brooklyn to be a convenient alternative to Manhattan to find housing.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] According to the 2020 Census, nearly 40,000 Indian Americans call Brooklyn home.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brighton Beach is home to a growing Pakistani American community, while Midwood is home to Little Pakistan along Coney Island Avenue recently renamed Muhammad Ali Jinnah way.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Pakistan Independence Day is celebrated every year with parades and parties on Coney Island Avenue.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn's Greek Americans live throughout the borough.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] A historical concentration has endured in Bay Ridge and adjacent areas, where there is a noticeable cluster of Hellenic-focused schools, businesses and cultural institutions.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Other businesses are situated in Downtown Brooklyn near Atlantic Avenue.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] As in much of the New York metropolitan area, Greek-owned diners are found throughout the borough.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn is home to a large and growing number of same-sex couples.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Same-sex marriages in New York were legalized on June 24, 2011, and were authorized to take place beginning 30 days thereafter.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] The Park Slope neighborhood spearheaded the popularity of Brooklyn among lesbians, and Prospect Heights has an LGBT residential presence.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Numerous neighborhoods have since become home to LGBT communities.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn Liberation March, the largest transgender-rights demonstration in LGBTQ history, took place on June 14, 2020, stretching from Grand Army Plaza to Fort Greene, focused on supporting Black transgender lives, drawing an estimated 15,000 to 20,000 participants.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Brooklyn became a preferred site for artists and hipsters to set up live/work spaces after being priced out of the same types of living arrangements in Manhattan.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] Various neighborhoods in Brooklyn, including Williamsburg, DUMBO, Red Hook, and Park Slope evolved as popular neighborhoods for artists-in-residence.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p01] However, rents and costs of living have since increased dramatically in these same neighborhoods, forcing artists to move to somewhat less expensive neighborhoods in Brooklyn or across Upper New York Bay to locales in New Jersey, such as Jersey City or Hoboken.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] At the 2020 census, 2,736,074 people lived in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The United States Census Bureau had estimated Brooklyn's population increased by 2.2% to 2,559,903 between 2010 and 2019.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn's estimated population represented 30.7% of New York City's estimated population of 8,336,817; 33.5% of Long Island's population of 7,701,172; and 13.2% of New York State's population of 19,542,209.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 2020, the government of New York City projected Brooklyn's population at 2,648,403.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The 2019 census estimates determined there were 958,567 households with an average of 2.66 persons per household.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] There were 1,065,399 housing units in 2019 and a median gross rent of $1,426.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Citing growth, Brooklyn gained 9,696 building permits at the 2019 census estimates program.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Hispanics and Latinos made up 18.9% of Brooklyn's population.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 2010, Brooklyn had some neighborhoods segregated based on race, ethnicity, and religion.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Overall, the southwest half of Brooklyn is racially mixed although it contains few black residents; the northeast section is mostly black and Hispanic/Latino.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn has a high degree of linguistic diversity.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In total, 45.9% (1,051,456) of Brooklyn's population ages 5 and older spoke a home language other than English.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn has played a major role in various aspects of American culture, including literature, cinema, and theater.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn's accent has often been portrayed as the "typical New Yorker accent" in American media, although this accent and its stereotypes are supposedly diminishing in currency.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn's official colors are blue and gold.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn hosts the world-renowned Brooklyn Academy of Music, the Brooklyn Philharmonic, and the second-largest public art collection in the United States, housed in the Brooklyn Museum.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Brooklyn Museum, opened in 1897, is New York City's second-largest public art museum.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] It has in its permanent collection more than 1.5 million objects, from ancient Egyptian masterpieces to contemporary art.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Brooklyn Children's Museum, the world's first museum dedicated to children, opened in December 1899.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The only such New York State institution accredited by the American Alliance of Museums, it is one of the few globally to have a permanent collection – over 30,000 cultural objects and natural history specimens.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Brooklyn Academy of Music (BAM) includes a 2,109-seat opera house, an 874-seat theater, and the art-house BAM Rose Cinemas.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Ann's Warehouse are on the other side of Downtown Brooklyn in the DUMBO arts district.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn Technical High School has the second-largest auditorium in New York City (after Radio City Music Hall), with a seating capacity of over 3,000.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn has several local newspapers: The *Brooklyn Daily Eagle*, *Bay Currents* (Oceanfront Brooklyn), *Brooklyn View*, *The Brooklyn Paper*, and Courier-Life Publications.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Courier-Life Publications, owned by Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation, is Brooklyn's largest chain of newspapers.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn is also served by the major New York dailies, including *The New York Times*, the *New York Daily News*, and the *New York Post*.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Several others are now defunct, including the *Brooklyn Union* (1867–1937), and the *Brooklyn Times*.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The borough is home to the arts and politics monthly *Brooklyn Rail*, as well as the arts and cultural quarterly *Cabinet*.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] *Hello Mr.* is also published in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] *El Diario La Prensa*, the largest and oldest Spanish-language daily newspaper in the United States, maintains its corporate headquarters at 1 MetroTech Center in Downtown Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Major ethnic publications include the Brooklyn–Queens Catholic paper *The Tablet*, *Hamodia*, an Orthodox Jewish daily, and *The Jewish Press*, an Orthodox Jewish weekly.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Many nationally distributed ethnic newspapers are based in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Over 60 ethnic groups, writing in 42 languages, publish some 300 non-English language magazines and newspapers in New York City.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Among them is the quarterly *L'Idea*, a bilingual magazine printed in Italian and English since 1974.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In addition, many newspapers published abroad, such as *The Daily Gleaner* and *The Star* of Jamaica, are available in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] *Our Time Press*, published weekly by DBG Media, covers the Village of Brooklyn with a motto of "The Local Paper with the Global View".
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The City of New York has an official television station, run by NYC Media, which features programming based in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn Community Access Television is the borough's public access channel.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Its studios are at the BRIC Arts Media venue, called BRIC House, located on Fulton Street in the Fort Greene section of the borough.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn's job market is driven by three main factors: the performance of the national and city economy, population flows and the borough's position as a convenient back office for New York's businesses.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Forty-four percent of Brooklyn's employed population, or 410,000 people, work in the borough; more than half of the borough's residents work outside its boundaries.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] As a result, economic conditions in Manhattan are important to the borough's jobseekers.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Strong international immigration to Brooklyn generates jobs in services, retailing and construction.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Jobs in the borough were traditionally concentrated in manufacturing, but since 1975, Brooklyn has shifted from a manufacturing-based to a service-based economy.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 2004, 215,000 Brooklyn residents worked in the services sector, while 27,500 worked in manufacturing.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Although manufacturing has declined, a substantial base has remained in apparel and niche manufacturing concerns such as furniture, fabricated metals, and food products.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The pharmaceutical company Pfizer was founded in Brooklyn in 1869 and had a manufacturing plant in the borough for many years that employed thousands of workers, but the plant shut down in 2008.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] However, new light-manufacturing concerns in packaging organic and high-end food have sprung up in the old plant.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Established as a shipbuilding facility in 1801, the Brooklyn Navy Yard employed 70,000 people at its peak during World War II and was then the largest employer in the borough.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The *Missouri*, the ship on which the Japanese formally surrendered, was built there, as was the *Maine*, whose sinking off Havana led to the start of the Spanish–American War.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The iron-sided Civil War vessel the *Monitor* was built in Greenpoint.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] From 1968 to 1979 Seatrain Shipbuilding was the major employer.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Later tenants include industrial design firms, food processing businesses, artisans, and the film and television production industry.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] About 230 private-sector firms providing 4,000 jobs are at the Yard.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Construction and services are the fastest-growing sectors.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Most employers in Brooklyn are small businesses.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 2000, 91% of the approximately 38,704 business establishments in Brooklyn had fewer than 20 employees.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] As of August 2008, the borough's unemployment rate was 5.9%.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn is also home to many banks and credit unions.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] According to the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation, there were 37 banks and 26 credit unions operating in the borough in 2010.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The rezoning of Downtown Brooklyn has generated over US$10 billion of private investment and $300 million in public improvements since 2004.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn is also attracting numerous high technology start-up companies, as Silicon Alley, the metonym for New York City's entrepreneurship ecosystem, has expanded from Lower Manhattan into Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn's major professional sports team is the NBA's Brooklyn Nets.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Nets moved into the borough in 2012, and play their home games at Barclays Center in Prospect Heights.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Previously, the Nets had played in Uniondale, New York and in New Jersey.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In April 2020, the New York Liberty of the WNBA were sold to the Nets' owners and moved their home venue from Madison Square Garden to the Barclays Center.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Barclays Center was also the home arena for the NHL's New York Islanders full-time from 2015 to 2018, then part-time from 2018 to 2020 (alternating with Nassau Coliseum in Uniondale).
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Islanders had originally played at Nassau Coliseum full-time since their inception until 2015 when their lease at the venue expired and the team moved to Barclays Center.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 2020, the team returned to Nassau Coliseum full-time for one season before moving to the UBS Arena in Elmont, New York in 2021.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn also has a storied sports history.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] It has been home to many famous sports figures such as Joe Paterno, Vince Lombardi, Mike Tyson, Zab Judah, Joe Torre, Sandy Koufax, Billy Cunningham and Vitas Gerulaitis.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Basketball legend Michael Jordan was born in Brooklyn though he grew up in Wilmington, North Carolina.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In the earliest days of organized baseball, Brooklyn teams dominated the new game.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The second recorded game of baseball was played near what is now Fort Greene Park on October 24, 1845.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn's Excelsiors, Atlantics and Eckfords were the leading teams from the mid-1850s through the Civil War, and there were dozens of local teams with neighborhood league play, such as at Mapleton Oval.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn's most famous historical team, the Brooklyn Dodgers, named for "trolley dodgers" played at Ebbets Field.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 1947 Jackie Robinson was hired by the Dodgers as the first African-American player in Major League Baseball in the modern era.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 1955, the Dodgers, perennial National League pennant winners, won the only World Series for Brooklyn against their rival New York Yankees.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The event was marked by mass euphoria and celebrations.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Just two years later, the Dodgers moved to Los Angeles.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Walter O'Malley, the team's owner at the time, is still vilified, even by Brooklynites too young to remember the Dodgers as Brooklyn's ball club.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] After a 43-year hiatus, professional baseball returned to the borough in 2001 with the Brooklyn Cyclones, a minor league team that plays in MCU Park in Coney Island.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] They are an affiliate of the New York Mets.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The minor-league New York Cosmos soccer club played its home games at MCU Park in 2017.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] A new Brooklyn FC will begin play in 2024, fielding a women's team in the first-division USL Super League and a men's team in the second-division USL Championship beginning in 2025.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn once had a National Football League team named the Brooklyn Lions in 1926, who played at Ebbets Field.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In rugby union, Rugby United New York joined Major League Rugby in 2019 and played their home games at MCU Park through the 2021 season.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn has one of the most active recreational fishing fleets in the United States.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In addition to a large private fleet along Jamaica Bay, there is a substantial public fleet within Sheepshead Bay.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Species caught include Black Fish, Porgy, Striped Bass, Black Sea Bass, Fluke, and Flounder.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Each of New York City's five counties, coterminous with each borough, has its own criminal court system and District Attorney, the chief public prosecutor who is directly elected by popular vote.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn has 16 City Council members, the largest number of any of the five boroughs.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Brooklyn Borough Government includes a borough president and a court, library, borough government board, head of borough government, deputy head of borough government and deputy borough government president.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn has 18 of the city's 59 community districts, each served by an unpaid community board with advisory powers under the city's Uniform Land Use Review Procedure.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Each board has a paid district manager who acts as an interlocutor with city agencies.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Kings County Democratic County Committee (aka the Brooklyn Democratic Party) is the county committee of the Democratic Party in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The United States Postal Service operates post offices in Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Brooklyn Main Post Office is located at 271 Cadman Plaza East in Downtown Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn has been a bastion of left-wing politics since before the turn of the 20th century; with its concentration of workers and immigrants, several socialist and labor parties have found purchase in the borough.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In the municipal and state elections of 1917, New York City elected ten assemblymen and seven aldermen of the Socialist Party; three of the assemblymen and two of the aldermen were from Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 1941, shortly before American entry into World War II, Brooklyn elected communist Peter V.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Cacchione to the City Council, making him the first open member of the Communist Party elected to public office in the state.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Following the 2025 New York City mayoral primary and general election, several neighborhoods in the borough have been identified as part of the so-called "Commie corridor," a region of the city strongly supportive of Zohran Mamdani and other Democratic Socialists.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] As is the case with sister boroughs Manhattan and the Bronx, Brooklyn has not voted for a Republican in a national presidential election since Calvin Coolidge in 1924.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In the 2008 presidential election, Democrat Barack Obama received 79.4% of the vote in Brooklyn while Republican John McCain received 20.0%.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 2012, Barack Obama increased his Democratic margin of victory in the borough, dominating Brooklyn with 82.0% of the vote to Republican Mitt Romney's 16.9%.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 2024, Republican Donald Trump reached 27% of the vote, and held Kamala Harris at just over 70%, a significant shift from Joe Biden's performance of over 76% in 2020.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] While still a decisive Democratic victory, this was the strongest Republican support in Brooklyn since 1988, and the largest number of raw Republican votes there since 1972.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] As of 2023, four Democrats and one Republican represented Brooklyn in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] One congressional district lies entirely within the borough.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn offers a wide array of private housing, as well as public housing, which is administered by the New York City Housing Authority (NYCHA).
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Affordable rental and co-operative housing units throughout the borough were created under the Mitchell–Lama Housing Program.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] There were 1,101,441 housing units in 2022 at an average density of 15,876 units per square mile (6,130/km2).
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Public housing administered by NYCHA accounts for more than 100,000 residents in nearly 50,000 units in 2023.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Education in Brooklyn is provided by a vast number of public and private institutions.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Non-charter public schools in the borough are managed by the New York City Department of Education, the largest public school system in the United States.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn Technical High School, commonly called Brooklyn Tech, a New York City public high school, is the largest specialized high school for science, mathematics, and technology in the United States.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn Tech is across the street from Fort Greene Park.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] This high school was built from 1930 to 1933 at a cost of about $6 million and is 12 stories high.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn Tech is noted for its famous alumni (including two Nobel Laureates), its academics, and a large number of graduates attending prestigious universities.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn College is a senior college of the City University of New York (CUNY), and was the first public coeducational liberal arts college in New York City.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The college ranked in the top 10 nationally for the second consecutive year in Princeton Review's 2006 guidebook, *America's Best Value Colleges*.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Many of its students are first and second-generation Americans.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Founded in 1970, Medgar Evers College is a senior college of the City University of New York.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The college offers programs at the baccalaureate and associate degree levels, as well as adult and continuing education classes for central Brooklyn residents, corporations, government agencies, and community organizations.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Medgar Evers College is a few blocks east of Prospect Park in Crown Heights.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] CUNY's New York City College of Technology (City Tech) of The City University of New York (Downtown Brooklyn/Brooklyn Heights) is the largest public college of technology in New York State and a national model for technological education.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Established in 1946, City Tech can trace its roots to 1881 when the Technical Schools of the Metropolitan Museum of Art were renamed the New York Trade School.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] That institution—which became the Voorhees Technical Institute many decades later—was soon a model for the development of technical and vocational schools worldwide.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 1971, Voorhees was incorporated into City Tech.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] SUNY Downstate College of Medicine, founded as the Long Island College Hospital in 1860, is the oldest hospital-based medical school in the United States.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Medical Center comprises the College of Medicine, College of Health Related Professions, College of Nursing, School of Public Health, School of Graduate Studies, and University Hospital of Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Half of the Medical Center's students are minorities or immigrants.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The College of Medicine has the highest percentage of minority students of any medical school in New York State.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Adelphi University, based in Garden City, moved its Manhattan Campus in 2023 to a new location on Livingston Street in Downtown Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The move marks a return to Brooklyn for the university, which originated on Adelphi Street with the Adelphi Academy.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Francis College, which has created a new campus at 179 Livingston Street.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn Law School was founded in 1901 and is notable for its diverse student body.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Women and African Americans were enrolled in 1909.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] According to the Leiter Report, a compendium of law school rankings published by Brian Leiter, Brooklyn Law School places 31st nationally for the quality of students.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Long Island University is a private university headquartered in Brookville on Long Island, with a campus in Downtown Brooklyn with 6,417 undergraduate students.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Brooklyn campus has strong science and medical technology programs, at the graduate and undergraduate levels.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Pratt Institute, in Clinton Hill, is a private college founded in 1887 with programs in engineering, architecture, and the arts.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Some buildings in the school's Brooklyn campus are official landmarks.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Pratt has over 4700 students, with most at its Brooklyn campus.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Graduate programs include a library and information science, architecture, and urban planning.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Undergraduate programs include architecture, construction management, writing, critical and visual studies, industrial design and fine arts, totaling over 25 programs in all.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The New York University Tandon School of Engineering, the United States' second oldest private institute of technology, founded in 1854, has its main campus in Downtown's MetroTech Center, a commercial, civic and educational redevelopment project of which it was a key sponsor.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] NYU-Tandon is one of the 18 schools and colleges that comprise New York University (NYU).
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Francis College is a Catholic college in Downtown Brooklyn founded in 1859 by Franciscan friars.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Over 2,400 students attend the small liberal arts college.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Francis is considered by *The New York Times* as one of the more diverse colleges, and was ranked one of the best baccalaureate colleges by *Forbes* magazine and *U.S.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn also has smaller liberal arts institutions, such as Saint Joseph's College in Clinton Hill and Boricua College in Williamsburg.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Kingsborough Community College is a junior college in the City University of New York system in Manhattan Beach.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] New York City College of Technology (City Tech) is a public college in New York City.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Founded in 1946, it is the City University of New York's college of technology.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Its main urban campus is located in Downtown Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] As an independent system, separate from the New York and Queens public library systems, the Brooklyn Public Library offers thousands of public programs, millions of books, and use of more than 850 free Internet-accessible computers.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] It also has books and periodicals in all the major languages spoken in Brooklyn, including English, Russian, Chinese, Spanish, Hebrew, and Haitian Creole, as well as French, Yiddish, Hindi, Bengali, Polish, Italian, and Arabic.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Central Library is a landmarked building facing Grand Army Plaza.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] There are 58 library branches, placing one within a half-mile of each Brooklyn resident.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] It will provide access and training to arts applications and technologies not widely available to the public.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The collections will include the subjects of art, theater, dance, music, film, photography, and architecture.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] A special archive will house the records and history of Brooklyn's arts communities.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In 2015, about 57 percent of all households in Brooklyn were households without automobiles.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The citywide rate is 55 percent in New York City.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn features extensive public transit.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Nineteen New York City Subway services, including the Franklin Avenue Shuttle, traverse the borough.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Approximately 92.8% of Brooklyn residents traveling to Manhattan use the subway, despite the fact some neighborhoods like Flatlands and Marine Park are poorly served by subway service.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Proposed New York City Subway lines never built include a line along Nostrand or Utica Avenues to Marine Park, as well as a subway line to Spring Creek.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn was once served by an extensive network of streetcars, but many were replaced by the public bus network that covers the entire borough.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] There is also daily express bus service into Manhattan.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] New York's famous yellow cabs also provide transportation in Brooklyn, although they are less numerous in the borough.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] There are three commuter rail stations in Brooklyn: East New York, Nostrand Avenue, and Atlantic Terminal, the terminus of the Atlantic Branch of the Long Island Rail Road.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The terminal is near the Atlantic Avenue–Barclays Center subway station, with ten connecting subway services.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In February 2015, Mayor Bill de Blasio announced that the city government would begin a citywide ferry service called NYC Ferry to extend ferry transportation to communities in the city that have been traditionally underserved by public transit.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The ferry opened in May 2017, with the Bay Ridge ferry serving southwestern Brooklyn and the East River Ferry serving northwestern Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] A third route, the Rockaway ferry, makes one stop in the borough at Brooklyn Army Terminal.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] A streetcar line, the Brooklyn–Queens Connector, was proposed by the city in February 2016, with the planned timeline calling for service to begin around 2024.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Other prominent roadways are the Prospect Expressway (New York State Route 27), the Belt Parkway, and the Jackie Robinson Parkway (formerly the Interborough Parkway).
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Planned expressways that were never built include the Bushwick Expressway, an extension of I-78 and the Cross-Brooklyn Expressway, I-878.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Major thoroughfares include Atlantic Avenue, Fourth Avenue, 86th Street, Kings Highway, Bay Parkway, Ocean Parkway, Eastern Parkway, Linden Boulevard, McGuinness Boulevard, Flatbush Avenue, Pennsylvania Avenue, and Nostrand Avenue.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Much of Brooklyn has only named streets, but Park Slope, Bay Ridge, Sunset Park, Bensonhurst, and Borough Park and the other western sections have numbered streets running approximately northwest to southeast, and numbered avenues going approximately northeast to southwest.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] East of Dahill Road, lettered avenues (like Avenue M) run east and west, and numbered streets have the prefix "East".
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] South of Avenue O, related numbered streets west of Dahill Road use the "West" designation.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] This set of numbered streets ranges from West 37th Street to East 108 Street, and the avenues range from A–Z with names substituted for some of them in some neighborhoods (notably Albemarle, Beverley, Cortelyou, Dorchester, Ditmas, Foster, Farragut, Glenwood, Quentin).
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Numbered streets prefixed by "North" and "South" in Williamsburg, and "Bay", "Beach", "Brighton", "Plumb", "Paerdegat" or "Flatlands" along the southern and southwestern waterfront are loosely based on the old grids of the original towns of Kings County that eventually consolidated to form Brooklyn.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] These names often reflect the bodies of water or beaches around them, such as Plumb Beach or Paerdegat Basin.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn is connected to Manhattan by three bridges, the Brooklyn, Manhattan, and Williamsburg Bridge; a vehicular tunnel, the Brooklyn–Battery Tunnel (also known as the Hugh L.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Carey Tunnel); and several subway tunnels.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Verrazzano–Narrows Bridge links Brooklyn with the more suburban borough of Staten Island.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Brooklyn was long a major shipping port, especially at the Brooklyn Army Terminal and Bush Terminal in Sunset Park.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Most container ship cargo operations have shifted to the New Jersey side of New York Harbor, while the Brooklyn Cruise Terminal in Red Hook is a focal point for New York's growing cruise industry.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The *Queen Mary 2*, one of the world's largest ocean liners, was designed specifically to fit under the Verrazzano–Narrows Bridge, the longest suspension bridge in the United States.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] She makes regular ports of call at the Red Hook terminal on her transatlantic crossings from Southampton, England.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The Brooklyn waterfront formerly employed tens of thousands of borough residents and acted as an incubator for industries across the entire city, and the decline of the port exacerbated Brooklyn's decline in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] In February 2015, Mayor Bill de Blasio announced that the city government would begin NYC Ferry to extend ferry transportation to traditionally underserved communities in the city.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The ferry opened in May 2017, offering commuter services from the western shore of Brooklyn to Manhattan via three routes.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The East River Ferry serves points in Lower Manhattan, Midtown, Long Island City, and northwestern Brooklyn via its East River route.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] The South Brooklyn and Rockaway routes serve southwestern Brooklyn before terminating in lower Manhattan.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] Ferries to Coney Island are also planned.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] SeaStreak also offers a weekday ferry service between the Brooklyn Army Terminal and the Manhattan ferry slips at Pier 11/Wall Street downtown and East 34th Street Ferry Landing in midtown.
[src:brooklyn/brooklyn-p02] A Cross-Harbor Rail Tunnel, originally proposed in the 1920s as a core project for the then-new Port Authority of New York is again being studied and discussed as a way to ease freight movements across a large swath of the metropolitan area.
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] The town of 's‑Gravenzande had 15,241 inhabitants in 2011.
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] The built-up area of the town was 2.7 km2 (1.0 sq mi), and contained 5,879 residences.
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] As of 1 January 2023, 's‑Gravenzande is the largest town in Westland with 23.470 inhabitants.
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] The former municipality of 's‑Gravenzande also included the township of Heenweg.
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] 's-Gravenzande is the only place in the Westland with a history as a town ("stad").
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] 's-Gravenzande was granted town rights ("stadsrechten") in 1246 by Count William II of Holland who, just like his father Count Floris IV, regularly resided at his estate near the town.
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] It is therefore the only town in Westland.
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] Machteld van Brabant, daughter of Duke Henry I and wife of Floris IV, was responsible for building the town's church, and gave it a Madonna statue to which miraculous powers were attributed.
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] 's-Gravenzande subsequently became a pilgrimage site.
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] The neighborhood of Gravesend, Brooklyn, New York in the United States is said by some to have been named for 's-Gravenzande.
[src:brooklyn/s-gravenzande] A 1656 Dutch map of Nova Belgica (New Netherland) confirms this, as it shows several Dutch names of towns like Vlissingen (Flushing), Breukelen (Brooklyn), Amersfoort (Flatlands), Heemstee (Hempstead) and Gravesant ('s-Gravenzande).
